g.text: ONE DAY I WILL RETURN TO YOUR SIDE: The graffito has been painted over the traces of the fight that took place here. It smells of blood and heavy fuel oil.
You: Say nothing. Stare grimly into the flames.
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant crouches, touching the fuel oil with his finger.
ONE DAY I WILL RETURN TO YOUR SIDE: The red-dyed fuel oil glistens. This was painted very recently.
ONE DAY I WILL RETURN TO YOUR SIDE: Slowly the flames subside, the fuel burning out. The air still smells of mazut -- and springtime.
You: Does this have anything to do with' The Return' Klaasje was waiting for?
Does this have anything to do with The Return Katarzine Alasije was waiting for?
You: Does this have anything to do with 'The Return' Klaasje is waiting for?
Does this have anything to do with The Return Katarzine Alasije is waiting for?
Interfacing: You *could* buy some smokes, light up a ciggy and throw it in there... You know, just to see what happens. See if it's flammable. It's better that way. Safer.
You: Looks like Cindy the SKULL has been here.
"Looks like Cindy the SKULL has been here."
You: No. Nope. No-no-no, bad idea.
Interfacing: Okay. Sorry. Hooh. Close call.
Conceptualization: Of what and to whom, you think? Spoken as the something that will one day return? Or as the someone who's waiting?
Inland Empire: The return to her side.
You: "Step back, lieutenant." (Set the graffito on fire with a lit cigarette.)
ONE DAY I WILL RETURN TO YOUR SIDE: The fuel oil catches fire immediately with an ominous hiss -- a bright orange flash across the surface of the letters. Black smoke rises from the burning message.
The fuel oil catches fire immediately, with a low hiss -- a bright orange flash across the surface of the lettering. Rain turns to vapour above the burning message, mingling with the black smoke.

The fuel oil catches fire immediately, with a low hiss -- a bright orange flash across the surface of the lettering. The falling snow turns to vapour above the burning message, mingling with the black smoke.
Conceptualization: Spoken as the something that will one day return? Or as the someone who's waiting?
Kim Kitsuragi: "Or some other hoodlum. This is still fresh. It wasn't here yesterday."

Kim Kitsuragi: "Could be. In Revachol West, someone somewhere is always whispering about Le Retour..." He squints his eyes at the writing. "It's an *aerograffito*, meant for Coalition aerostatics in the lower troposphere."
Interfacing: Heavy fuel oil -- isn't that... flammable?
You: Set the graffito on fire with a lit cigarette.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Let's go to that island."
Kim Kitsuragi: "Time to crack this case. Let's really, really have a close look at that window in Klaasje's room."
Inland Empire: Fresh blood. The return to her side.
ONE DAY I WILL RETURN TO YOUR SIDE: The flames warm your face. Then -- a gust of cold wind, and the fire falters...
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant crouches, touching the fuel oil with his finger.
Shivers: IT'S TIME TO GO TO THE ISLAND.
Logic: It's time to crack this case. The next logical move is to go back upstairs, to Klaasje's room. Really inspect that window.
You: "Does this have anything to do with 'The Return' Klaasje was waiting for?"
"Does this have anything to do with The Return our Katarzine Alasije was waiting for?"
"Does this have anything to do with The Return our Miss Oranje was waiting for?"
You: "Does this have anything to do with 'The Return' Klaasje is waiting for?"
"Does this have anything to do with The Return our Katarzine Alasije is waiting for?"
"Does this have anything to do with The Return our Miss Oranje is waiting for?"
Inland Empire: What if the words are not directed at the people of Martinaise, or even the Coalition aerostatics above the city -- they're meant for something above even those...
Kim Kitsuragi: The lieutenant has taken a small step back. He looks at your face illuminated by the flames and nods silently. Then the fire falters...
Empathy: The flames warmed him too. Not at all in a bad way.
You: What are you trying to imply, fingers?
ONE DAY I WILL RETURN TO YOUR SIDE: And blood. Some of it may even be yours. Looks like a giant mop was used to turn it into lettering...
You: I smell heavy fuel oil.
Kim Kitsuragi: "Looks like it, yes. This is still fresh. It wasn't here yesterday."
You: Looks like Cindy the SKULL finally found the words for her masterpiece.
"Looks like Cindy the SKULL finally found the words for her masterpiece."
Kim Kitsuragi: "And blood. Some of it is even yours."
Reaction Speed: This was Cindy the SKULL.
